        <property propertyId="67f102e2-9cb6-4d20-aa16-bf74d8a03326" amount="1.0" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
          <name xml:lang="en">wet mass</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
          <comment xml:lang="en">The waste contains 1kg polyurethane</comment>
        </property>
        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">Estimated value. The EU market for sealants in 2012 was of 533.860 thousand tons of sealants, more than 50% of this is constituted by silicon and polyurethane (ASI 2013). The percentage of polyurethane sealant (14%) and polyurethane foam (13%) are taken from Nerlfi et al. (2013). 
The CH production volume is extrapolated from the EU production volume using the nominal GDP of 2005 (source: United Nations, http://data.un.org/Glossary.aspx?q=GDP+%28current+US%24%29, accessed 20130726 and 20130312). Where EU GDP is 33% of the world and the CH GDP is 0.8% of the world.
As the main application of this material is in the construction sector, the rate of waste production is assumed to be 15% (taken from the estimated value for gypsum (WRAP, n.d). 
The treatment route is taken from Hincapié et al. (2015) for the category of combustible waste (which includes sealants), where 28% is sent to recycling, 64% incineration, and 8% landfill. 

ASI (2013) Market Trends: Sealant Demand Growing in Europe. The construction industry continues to control the demand for sealants. Retrieved from: &lt;http://www.adhesivesmag.com/articles/92423-market-trends-sealant-demand-growing-in-europe&gt;, accessed 9th May 2016 
Steven Nerlfi, Minesh Kusumgar and Michael Growney (2013) The Global Sealants Industry. Paint and Coatings Industry (PCI) (http://www.pcimag.com/articles/97675-the-global-sealants-market, accessed 20160122)
WRAP (n.d.) International practice in plasterboard recycling: Canada. Retrieved from: http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Case%20study%20-%20Plasterboard%20recycling%20in%20Canada.pdf, accessed 3 May 2016
Ingrid Hincapié, Alejandro Caballero-Guzmán, Bernd Nowack (2015) Nanomaterials in Landfills Module 3: Nanomaterials in Construction Waste. EMPA, Swiss Federal Laboratories for Materials Science and Technology. St. Gallen, Switzerland</productionVolumeComment>
